    "initial position annotation": "Key Concepts:\nIn the opening, a central horse is generally superior to an edge horse, and an edge horse is superior to a corner horse; likewise, two central horses are usually superior to two edge horses.\nIn Central Cannon openings, the cannon's defensive influence extends to the opposite side of the board, so a side chariot should generally target the horse on the cannon side.\nMulti-purpose pawn advance.\nPlans should be carried out consistently; otherwise, one often ends up at a disadvantage.\nIn the opening, a chariot is generally counted as having gained at most three tempos regardless of where it goes.\nA horse placed directly in front of the king is generally considered a poor formation and should not remain there for long."
